Last Revision: 04/05/2019

Author(s): Lee Ping Tay - joylp.tay@gmail.com

Description:

Source of Data: The Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System (IPEDS) by the National Center for Education Statistics (NCES) in United States. (https://nces.ed.gov/ipeds/datacenter/DataFiles.aspx)

Goal: This R script is used to perform exploratory data analysis and data visualization on higher eduacation data. Bar graphs on most expensive and least expensive colleges were created. Linear Regression and Residuals Analysis were conducted to identify associations between Tuition Fees and Admission Rate.

Contents: Libraries and Environment Data Import and Preprocessing Data Manipulation (Merge dataframes) Exploratory Data Analysis / Data Visualization Linear Regression Residuals analysis

############################################################################################### Linear Regression ############################################################################################### fit the model

plot(df_ipeds_adm$CHG2AY3 ~ df_ipeds_adm$adm_rate , xlab="Admission Rate", 
     ylab="In-State Tuition and Fees", main="Tuition and Fees vs Admission Rate", 
     col="blue")

tuitionfit_adm <- lm(formula = df_ipeds_adm$CHG2AY3 ~ df_ipeds_adm$adm_rate)
abline(tuitionfit_adm, col="red")

############################################################################################### Residuals analysis ############################################################################################### diagnostic plot Plot the model information par(mfrow = c(2, 2))

plot(tuitionfit_adm, cex.lab = 1.5, cex.axis = 1.5, col="blue")

We must test these three assumptions after calculating the coefficients in the linear regression equation using the residuals:

Residuals or errors are normally distributed Residuals or errors have a constant variance Residuals or errors are independent of one another (not relevant to our scenario) We use residual analysis to determine whether or not these conditions have been met. Interpretation of the diagnostic plot 1. Residuals vs Fitted - shows if residuals have non-linear patterns. We examine if the residuals exhibit homoscedasticity or approximately constant variance across the predicted values of the dependent variable. In this plot, Residuals are almost symmetrically distributed before observations pass 30000. But there is no distinctive pattern. 2. Normal Q-Q - shows if residuals are normally distributed. Residuals lined well on the dotted line except a few observations at the two ends. 3. Scale-Location - shows if residuals are spread equally along the ranges of predictors. The line is almost horizontal and residuals appear randomly spread. 4. Residuals vs Leverage - find influential cases if any. Cook's distance" measure the influence of each observation on the regression coefficients. There is no influential case as we can barely see Cook’s distance lines (a red dashed line) because almost all cases are well inside of the Cook’s distance lines. obtain predicted and residual values (differences between each data point and linear model)

df_ipeds_adm  <- df_ipeds_adm %>% 
                  mutate(predicted = predict(tuitionfit_adm),
                         residuals = residuals(tuitionfit_adm))

df_ipeds_adm$predicted <- predict(tuitionfit_adm) df_ipeds_adm$residuals <- residuals(tuitionfit_adm)

df_ipeds_adm %>% select(CHG2AY3, predicted, residuals) %>% head()

We can also use errors to look at Normality

df_ipeds_adm <- df_ipeds_adm %>% 
                 mutate(err=(CHG2AY3 - predicted) / CHG2AY3)

Homoscedasticity or heteroscedastic visually test the constant variance assumption

tuitionfitted_adm <- fitted(tuitionfit_adm)

plot(tuitionfitted_adm, df_ipeds_adm$residuals, xlab="residuals", 
     ylab="Predicted In-state Tuition and Fees", col="blue")

The graph shows a slightly different vertical height across the point cloud.
